Introduction
Machine learning with texts is one of the biggest interdisciplinary
areas in computational text analysis.
Another area that is quite lively—and stretches across disciplines
ranging from statistical physics and computer science to sociology
and political science—is network science.
For the next few class sessions, we will talk about the application of
network analysis to text data—i.e., text networks.
Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 March 25, 2019 2 / 30
Before We Get to Text Networks...
Before we get into text networks, however, it is important to get a
grasp with what networks are and what we can do with them.
As such, we are going to set aside texts for today and just get
acquainted with thinking in terms of networks.

From Attributes to Relations
So far, most of our analyses have been focused on drawing conclusions
about documents given their attributes:
The words in that document.
Who the author is.
When it was written.
How positive/negative its sentiment.
The topics it engages in.
Etc.
Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 March 25, 2019 4 / 30
From Attributes to Relations
With networks, we focus less on drawing conclusions based (purely) on
attributes. Instead, we draw attention to patterns based on relations
between documents in a corpus:
How similar one document is to another.
Which documents bridge across topics.
Which writers are “peripheral” writers.
Which document producers exert the most
inﬂuence over others.
Extent to which some documents cluster
together over time.
Etc.
Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 March 25, 2019 5 / 30

Relations as a Unit of Analysis
Why are relations an important unit of analysis?
Emirbayer’s “Manifesto for a Relational Sociology” (1997):
substantialist vs. relational thinking
discrete variables vs. patterns of association
attribute vs. interaction
substance vs. process
“Individual persons . . . are inseparable from the transactional contexts
within which they are embedded . . . [S]tructures are empty abstractions
apart from the several elements of which they are composed; societies
themselves are nothing but pluralities of associated individuals”
(1997:287-288).
Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 March 25, 2019 7 / 30
Relations as a Unit of Analysis
The idea is that many of the structured patterns in the world are
accounted for by the relations and interactions between elements
rather than within the elements themselves.
Some examples:
Disease contagion
Geneologies
Gene co-expression
Diﬀusion of market products
Social media sites
Your nervous system
Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 March 25, 2019 8 / 30
Relations as a Unit of Analysis
A network, then, is simply the structure of elements and the
relations that connect them to one another. Networks are everywhere:
there are biological networks, economic networks, social networks, neural
networks, and so on.
Some examples:
Disease contagion
Geneologies
Gene co-expression
Diﬀusion of market products
Social media sites
Your nervous system
Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 March 25, 2019 9 / 30
Relations as a Unit of Analysis
Without understanding the patterns of association between elements in
each of these networks (and the conditions under which these associations
arise and/or go away), it’s impossible to understand how these processes
work. Thus the importance of studying relations as a unit of analysis.
Some examples:
Disease contagion
Geneologies
Gene co-expression
Diﬀusion of market products
Social media sites
Your nervous system
Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 March 25, 2019 10 / 30
Vertices and Edges
So, what “constitutes” a network?
Every network is composed of two basic items: vertices and edges.
In a text network, vertices are usually documents. Edges (or ties) are
whatever we are using to connect documents—say, the extent of
vocabulary overlap.
Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 March 25, 2019 11 / 30

The Power of Networks/Graphs
If you can formulate a dataset as constituting a set of patterns of
association, you can leverage graph theory to analyze the formal
(structural) properties of those patterns. Such as:
The extent to which resources (e.g., material goods, information) can
ﬂow through a network (e.g., across highways connecting factories, or
email chains connecting employees).
The extent to which elements in a network tend to cluster into
more-or-less isolated “cliques.”
The extent to which there is homophily (e.g., the likelihood that a
person of a certain socioeconomic position is more likely to cohabitate
with, date, or marry another person of the same position).
If there are any isolates (e.g., a text document that has no word
overlap with any other documents in a corpus).
Identify “brokers” (e.g., managers who oversee two departments that
do not have any other points of connection between them).
Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 March 25, 2019 15 / 30
Matrices and Graphs
When I say that any dataset can be conceptualized as a network, I mean it!
Graphs are just visual representations of matrices.
So all of those document-term and term co-occurrence matrices we’ve
been working with can also be represented as networks!
Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 March 25, 2019 16 / 30

As a bit of a teaser for what we can do once we conceptualize our data in
terms of relations, we can color the vertices by their betweenness
centrality. This is a measure of the extent to which network resources
“ﬂow” through each vertex. In this case, betweenness measures the extent
to which each worker connects lower-level workers to higher-level workers.
The idea is that these workers occupy important structural positions
because they are the people through which important information passes.

Whose Important in the Chain of Command?
No surprise that worker #14 has the largest betweenness centrality, right?
They have the most employees under them; they connect those seven
workers to all other workers in the network. It is through worker #14 that
the ideas/information/resources of those seven employees reach the top
manager (#7), and presumably the other departments at the ﬁrm.

Conclusion
We’ll talk in more detail about betweenness centrality (and other network
properties) on Wednesday, speciﬁcally in the context of text networks.
The goal for today was simply to get you “thinking relationally”: that is,
in terms of networks.
For those of you interesting in networks more generally, consider taking the
social networks class in the sociology department!
